    <section title="5G Architectural Requriements on User Plane">
       <section title="General">
         <t>
         The 5G system provides date connectivity and services. The functionalities on user plane assumed in 
         are listed below:
           <list style="numbers">
             <t>Connection of IPv4, IPv6, Ethernet and Unstructured PDU</t>     <!-- 3.1 -->
             <t>UE mobility</t>                                                 <!-- 5.3.4 -->
             <t>Multi-homing for anchor UPFs</t>                                <!-- 5.6.4, 5.6.9.2.1~3 -->
             <t>Flexible UPF selection for PDU Sessions</t>                     <!-- 6.3.3 -->
             <t>QoS control</t>                                                 <!-- 5.7 -->
             <t>Policy and charging control</t>                                 <!-- 5.2.6 -->
             <t>Lawful Inspection</t>                                           <!-- 5.2.7 -->
             <t>Identifablity</t>                                               <!-- 5.9 -->
           </list>
         </t>
           
         <t>
         5G system is potentially defined as a service-based architecture, and PDU sessions are available to 
         be controlled from other authorized network functions via control plane functions.
         </t>
           
         <t>
         In addition, 5GS supports network slicing concept. A network slice is a logical network structured 
         of some of network function instances and required resources, and provides special network capabilities 
         and network characteristics. PDU sessions are allocated to the appropriate network slice by AMF 
         depending on their own subscription information. In each network slice, the some of functionality of 
         5GS user plane are also provided.
         </t>
       </section>
